{"repo": "django-money/django-money", "pull_number": 800, "instance_id": "django-money__django-money-800", "issue_numbers": [623], "base_commit": "53ab77e85d6d0c4588e2a8c87249110154e03845", "patch": "diff --git a/README.rst b/README.rst\nindex 7854a97cb..221f83fa4 100644\n--- a/README.rst\n+++ b/README.rst\n@@ -100,6 +100,66 @@ Caution: this setting also affects the initial migration of the `exchange` plugi\n the initial migration has no effect. (You'd need to `manage migrate exchange zero` and migrate again if you want\n to change it).\n \n+Callable defaults\n+-----------------\n+\n+.. versionadded:: 3.6.0\n+   Callables were introduced in 3.6.0 and did not work before.\n+\n+To make things configurable through project settings (especially useful for third-party applications using\n+django-money), you can wrap configurable defaults in a callable. This avoids generating migrations on models when the\n+defaults change!\n+\n+You can define a `default callable <https://docs.djangoproject.com/en/5.2/ref/models/fields/#default>`__ for your\n+MoneyField defaults, both money and separate currency. Here is an example:\n+\n+.. code:: python\n+\n+        from django.conf import settings\n+        from django.db import models\n+        from djmoney.models.fields import MoneyField\n+        from djmoney.money import Money\n+\n+        def get_default_currency():\n+            return settings.MY_DEFAULT_CURRENCY\n+\n+        def get_default_zero():\n+            return Money(\"0.00\", settings.MY_DEFAULT_CURRENCY)\n+\n+        class Product(models.Model):\n+            # The price has no default value, but a default currency is defined!\n+            price = MoneyField(max_digits=10, decimals=2, currency_default=get_default_currency)\n+            # Discount field defaults to 0 Money and thus does not need a default currency (it's in the Money\n+            # value supplied by get_default_zero\n+            discount = MoneyField(max_digits=10, decimals=2, default=get_default_zero)\n+\n+\n+Note that the supplied callables are subject to Django's internals and the fact that they need to be serializable for\n+the migration framework.\n+\n+Configuring currency choices\n+----------------------------\n+\n+It's possible to supply a global Django project setting for ``CURRENCY_CHOICES``, but you may also supply this as an\n+individual ``currency_choices`` option for MoneyFields:\n+\n+.. code:: python\n+\n+        from django.conf import settings\n+        from django.db import models\n+        from djmoney.models.fields import MoneyField\n+\n+        class Invoice(models.Model):\n+            # Allow 2 different currencies for total amount\n+            total_amount = MoneyField(max_digits=15, decimal_places=2, currency_choices=[(\"CLY\", \"CLY\"), (\"USD\", \"USD\")])\n+            # Only allow 1 currency in the accounted field\n+            converted_amount = MoneyField(max_digits=15, decimal_places=2, currency_choices=[(\"CLY\", \"CLY\")])\n+\n+As with other Django Field ``choices`` kwargs, you can also supply a callable for ``currency_choices`` (but not a\n+lambda). Please note that - similar to other ``choices`` fields - there are NO database constraints implied by this\n+option, so you need may need additional validation safeguards and\n+`adding your own db constraints <https://adamj.eu/tech/2020/01/22/djangos-field-choices-dont-constrain-your-data/>`__.\n+\n Field validation\n ----------------\n \ndiff --git a/djmoney/__init__.py b/djmoney/__init__.py\nindex 7a829927f..372ccd70e 100644\n--- a/djmoney/__init__.py\n+++ b/djmoney/__init__.py\n@@ -1,1 +1,1 @@\n-__version__ = \"3.5.4\"\n+__version__ = \"3.6.0b1\"\ndiff --git a/djmoney/models/fields.py b/djmoney/models/fields.py\nindex aee97f085..42f9f0007 100644\n--- a/djmoney/models/fields.py\n+++ b/djmoney/models/fields.py\n@@ -168,6 +168,10 @@ def contribute_to_class(self, cls, name):\n class MoneyField(models.DecimalField):\n     description = \"A field which stores both the currency and amount of money.\"\n \n+    @property\n+    def non_db_attrs(self):\n+        return super().non_db_attrs + (\"default_currency\", \"currency_choices\")\n+\n     def __init__(\n         self,\n         verbose_name=None,\n@@ -184,7 +188,9 @@ def __init__(\n     ):\n         nullable = kwargs.get(\"null\", False)\n         default = self.setup_default(default, default_currency, nullable)\n-        if not default_currency and default not in (None, NOT_PROVIDED):\n+\n+        # Provide the default currency from the default Money instance provided\n+        if not default_currency and isinstance(default, Money):\n             default_currency = default.currency\n \n         self.currency_max_length = currency_max_length\n@@ -198,8 +204,24 @@ def __init__(\n         Field.creation_counter += 1\n \n     def setup_default(self, default, default_currency, nullable):\n-        if default in (None, NOT_PROVIDED) or isinstance(default, Money):\n+        # None and NOT_PROVIDED are returned as-is\n+        if default in (None, NOT_PROVIDED):\n+            return default\n+        # Money instances need no further processing\n+        elif isinstance(default, Money):\n             return default\n+        # Callables continue to be callables (will be evaluated later)\n+        # Evaluating them here will create new migrations every time the callable returns a new value\n+        elif callable(default):\n+            return default\n+        # This is not supported: If default_currency is a callable, we need to fail, we cannot call it to construct the\n+        # default, that would have unintended consequences. Require to have BOTH default and default_currency as\n+        # callables in that case.\n+        elif callable(default_currency) and default_currency != NOT_PROVIDED:\n+            raise ValueError(\n+                \"django-money does not support a callable for default_currency, if the amount's default isn't also a \"\n+                \"callable.\"\n+            )\n         elif isinstance(default, (str, bytes)):\n             try:\n                 # handle scenario where default is formatted like:\n@@ -306,7 +328,10 @@ def formfield(self, **kwargs):\n         defaults[\"currency_choices\"] = self.currency_choices\n         defaults[\"default_currency\"] = self.default_currency\n         if self._has_default:\n-            defaults[\"default_amount\"] = self.default.amount\n+            if callable(self.default):\n+                defaults[\"default_amount\"] = self.default().amount\n+            else:\n+                defaults[\"default_amount\"] = self.default.amount\n         return super().formfield(**defaults)\n \n     def value_to_string(self, obj):\n@@ -316,13 +341,10 @@ def value_to_string(self, obj):\n     def deconstruct(self):\n         name, path, args, kwargs = super().deconstruct()\n \n-        if self._has_default:\n-            kwargs[\"default\"] = self.default.amount\n+        # Comment needed: Why is this done?\n         if self.default_currency != DEFAULT_CURRENCY:\n-            if self.default_currency is not None:\n-                kwargs[\"default_currency\"] = str(self.default_currency)\n-            else:\n-                kwargs[\"default_currency\"] = None\n+            kwargs[\"default_currency\"] = self.default_currency\n+        # Comment needed: Why is this done?\n         if self.currency_choices != CURRENCY_CHOICES:\n             kwargs[\"currency_choices\"] = self.currency_choices\n         if self.currency_field_name:\ndiff --git a/docs/changes.rst b/docs/changes.rst\nindex e80f161ca..263eb6cfa 100644\n--- a/docs/changes.rst\n+++ b/docs/changes.rst\n@@ -2,6 +2,18 @@ Changelog\n =========\n \n \n+`3.6b1`_ - 2025-08-31\n+---------------------\n+\n+**Added**\n+\n+- Support for callable ``default`` and ``currency_default``, and ``currency_choices`` :github-issue:`683` (:github-user:`benjaoming`)\n+- Add ``backend`` kwarg to ``convert_money`` function :github-issue:`787` (:github-user:`heckad`)\n+\n+**Changed**\n+\n+- Migrate to pyproject.toml and uv :github-issue:`791` (:github-user:`browniebroke`)\n+\n `3.5.4`_ - 2025-04-17\n ---------------------\n \n@@ -854,8 +866,7 @@ wrapping with ``money_manager``.\n \n - Initial public release\n \n-# .. _3.5: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5...HEAD\n-\n+.. _3.6b1: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.6.0b1...HEAD\n .. _3.5.4: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5.4...3.5.3\n .. _3.5.3: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5.3...3.5.2\n .. _3.5.2: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5.2...3.5.1\n", "test_patch": "diff --git a/tests/migrations/test_migrations.py b/tests/migrations/test_migrations.py\nindex 90fa96312..25984567f 100644\n--- a/tests/migrations/test_migrations.py\n+++ b/tests/migrations/test_migrations.py\n@@ -45,7 +45,7 @@ def make_models(self, content):\n         fd = self.project_root.join(\"models.py\")\n         fd.write(dedent(content))\n \n-    def make_migration(self, **fields):\n+    def make_migration(self, callable_default='Money(\"0.00 USD\")', **fields):\n         \"\"\"\n         Creates a model with provided fields and creates a migration for it.\n         \"\"\"\n@@ -57,12 +57,17 @@ def make_migration(self, **fields):\n             \"\"\"\n             from django.db import models\n \n-            from djmoney.models.fields import MoneyField\n+            from djmoney.models.fields import MoneyField, Money\n \n+            # A callable default\n+            def default1():\n+                return {callable_default}\n \n             class Model(models.Model):\n-                %s\"\"\"\n-            % fields_definition\n+                {fields}\n+            \"\"\".format(\n+                fields=fields_definition, callable_default=callable_default\n+            )\n         )\n         tests_path = os.path.dirname(os.path.dirname(tests.__file__))\n         return self.run(\n@@ -179,6 +184,60 @@ def test_alter_field(self):\n         assert operations[0].field.max_digits == 15\n         self.assert_migrate()\n \n+    def test_alter_field_callable(self):\n+        \"\"\"Test that changing the return value of a callable does not produce new migrations.\"\"\"\n+        self.make_default_migration()\n+        # Change the field to have a callable default\n+        migration = self.make_migration(\n+            field=\"MoneyField(max_digits=15, decimal_places=2, null=True, default=default1)\"\n+        )\n+        migration.stdout.fnmatch_lines(\n+            [\"*Migrations for 'money_app':*\", \"*0002_test.py*\", \"*Alter field field on model*\"]\n+        )\n+\n+        # Change the return value of the callable\n+        migration = self.make_migration(\n+            callable_default='\"USD\"', field=\"MoneyField(max_digits=15, decimal_places=2, null=True, default=default1)\"\n+        )\n+        migration.stdout.fnmatch_lines([\"No changes detected in app 'money_app'\"])\n+\n+    def test_alter_field_currency_callable(self):\n+        \"\"\"Test that changing the return value of a callable does not produce new migrations.\"\"\"\n+        self.make_default_migration()\n+        # Change the field to have a callable default\n+        migration = self.make_migration(\n+            field=\"MoneyField(max_digits=15, decimal_places=2, null=True, default_currency=default1)\"\n+        )\n+        migration.stdout.fnmatch_lines(\n+            [\"*Migrations for 'money_app':*\", \"*0002_test.py*\", \"*Alter field field on model*\"]\n+        )\n+\n+        # Change the return value of the callable\n+        migration = self.make_migration(\n+            callable_default='\"USD\"',\n+            field=\"MoneyField(max_digits=15, decimal_places=2, null=True, default_currency=default1)\",\n+        )\n+        migration.stdout.fnmatch_lines([\"No changes detected in app 'money_app'\"])\n+\n+    def test_alter_field_currency_choices_callable(self):\n+        \"\"\"Test that changing the return value of a callable does not produce new migrations.\"\"\"\n+        self.make_default_migration()\n+        # Change the field to have a callable default\n+        migration = self.make_migration(\n+            callable_default='[(\"USD\", \"USD\")]',\n+            field=\"MoneyField(max_digits=15, decimal_places=2, null=True, currency_choices=default1)\",\n+        )\n+        migration.stdout.fnmatch_lines(\n+            [\"*Migrations for 'money_app':*\", \"*0002_test.py*\", \"*Alter field field on model*\"]\n+        )\n+\n+        # Change the return value of the callable\n+        migration = self.make_migration(\n+            callable_default='[(\"CNY\", \"CNY\")]',\n+            field=\"MoneyField(max_digits=15, decimal_places=2, null=True, currency_choices=default1)\",\n+        )\n+        migration.stdout.fnmatch_lines([\"No changes detected in app 'money_app'\"])\n+\n     def test_remove_field(self):\n         self.make_default_migration()\n         migration = self.make_migration()\ndiff --git a/tests/settings.py b/tests/settings.py\nindex 2a909142c..ab4798ce6 100644\n--- a/tests/settings.py\n+++ b/tests/settings.py\n@@ -43,3 +43,8 @@\n \n OPEN_EXCHANGE_RATES_APP_ID = \"test\"\n FIXER_ACCESS_KEY = \"test\"\n+\n+DEFAULT_CURRENCY = \"USD\"\n+\n+# Additional setting for callables with different defaults\n+TEST_DEFAULT_CURRENCY = \"EUR\"\ndiff --git a/tests/test_form.py b/tests/test_form.py\nindex 4aae4fc1b..8c509d9d6 100644\n--- a/tests/test_form.py\n+++ b/tests/test_form.py\n@@ -20,6 +20,10 @@\n     MoneyForm,\n     MoneyFormMultipleCurrencies,\n     MoneyModelForm,\n+    MoneyModelFormWithCallableCurrencyChoices,\n+    MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefault,\n+    MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefaultAndCallableDefaultCurrency,\n+    MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefaultCurrency,\n     MoneyModelFormWithValidation,\n     NullableModelForm,\n     OptionalMoneyForm,\n@@ -28,7 +32,14 @@\n     PreciseModelForm,\n     ValidatedMoneyModelForm,\n )\n-from .testapp.models import ModelWithVanillaMoneyField, NullMoneyFieldModel\n+from .testapp.models import (\n+    ModelWithCallableCurrencyChoices,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefault,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefaultAndDefaultCurrency,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefaultCurrency,\n+    ModelWithVanillaMoneyField,\n+    NullMoneyFieldModel,\n+)\n \n \n pytestmark = pytest.mark.django_db\n@@ -45,6 +56,63 @@ def test_save():\n     assert money == retrieved.money\n \n \n+def test_save_with_callable_default():\n+    \"\"\"Test if the callable default triggers\"\"\"\n+    expected_money = Money(Decimal(\"0\"), \"EUR\")\n+    form = MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefault({})\n+\n+    assert form.is_valid()\n+    instance = form.save()\n+\n+    retrieved = ModelWithCallableDefault.objects.get(pk=instance.pk)\n+    assert expected_money == retrieved.money\n+\n+\n+def test_save_with_callable_default_currency():\n+    \"\"\"Test if the callable default triggers\"\"\"\n+    expected_money = Money(Decimal(\"10\"), \"EUR\")\n+    form = MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefaultCurrency({\"money_0\": \"10\", \"money_1\": \"EUR\"})\n+\n+    assert form.fields[\"money\"].initial[0] is None\n+    assert form.fields[\"money\"].initial[1]() == \"EUR\"\n+    assert \"\"\"<option value=\"EUR\" selected>\"\"\" in form.as_p()\n+    assert form.is_valid()\n+\n+    instance = form.save()\n+\n+    retrieved = ModelWithCallableDefaultCurrency.objects.get(pk=instance.pk)\n+    assert expected_money == retrieved.money\n+\n+\n+def test_save_with_callable_default_and_currency():\n+    \"\"\"Test if the callable defaults trigger when both are defined\"\"\"\n+    expected_money = Money(Decimal(\"0\"), \"EUR\")\n+    form = MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefaultAndCallableDefaultCurrency({})\n+\n+    assert form.is_valid()\n+    instance = form.save()\n+\n+    retrieved = ModelWithCallableDefaultAndDefaultCurrency.objects.get(pk=instance.pk)\n+    assert expected_money == retrieved.money\n+\n+\n+def test_save_with_callable_currency_choices():\n+    \"\"\"Test if the callable default triggers\"\"\"\n+    expected_money = Money(Decimal(\"10\"), \"EUR\")\n+    form = MoneyModelFormWithCallableCurrencyChoices({\"money_0\": \"10\", \"money_1\": \"EUR\"})\n+\n+    assert form.fields[\"money\"].initial[0] is None\n+    assert form.fields[\"money\"].initial[1]() == \"EUR\"\n+    assert list(form.fields[\"money\"].widget.widgets[1].choices) == [(\"DKK\", \"DKK\"), (\"EUR\", \"EUR\"), (\"USD\", \"USD\")]\n+    assert \"\"\"<option value=\"EUR\" selected>\"\"\" in form.as_p()\n+    assert form.is_valid()\n+\n+    instance = form.save()\n+\n+    retrieved = ModelWithCallableCurrencyChoices.objects.get(pk=instance.pk)\n+    assert expected_money == retrieved.money\n+\n+\n def test_validate():\n     money = Money(Decimal(\"10\"), \"SEK\")\n     form = MoneyForm({\"money_0\": money.amount, \"money_1\": money.currency})\ndiff --git a/tests/test_models.py b/tests/test_models.py\nindex 70b76c241..e3119a9cd 100644\n--- a/tests/test_models.py\n+++ b/tests/test_models.py\n@@ -32,6 +32,10 @@\n     InheritorModel,\n     ModelIssue300,\n     ModelRelatedToModelWithMoney,\n+    ModelWithCallableCurrencyChoices,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefault,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefaultAndDefaultCurrency,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefaultCurrency,\n     ModelWithChoicesMoneyField,\n     ModelWithCustomDefaultManager,\n     ModelWithCustomManager,\n@@ -78,6 +82,10 @@ class TestVanillaMoneyField:\n             (ModelWithDefaultAsString, {}, Money(\"123\", \"PLN\")),\n             (ModelWithDefaultAsInt, {}, Money(\"123\", \"GHS\")),\n             (ModelWithDefaultAsDecimal, {}, Money(\"0.01\", \"CHF\")),\n+            (ModelWithCallableDefault, {}, Money(\"0.00\", \"EUR\")),  # noqa\n+            (ModelWithCallableDefaultCurrency, {\"money\": 0}, Money(\"0.00\", \"EUR\")),\n+            (ModelWithCallableDefaultAndDefaultCurrency, {}, Money(\"0.00\", \"EUR\")),\n+            (ModelWithCallableCurrencyChoices, {\"money\": Money(\"0.00\", \"DKK\")}, Money(\"0.00\", \"DKK\")),\n             (CryptoModel, {\"money\": Money(10, \"USDT\")}, Money(10, \"USDT\")),\n         ),\n     )\ndiff --git a/tests/testapp/forms.py b/tests/testapp/forms.py\nindex 99c2e44ce..1731e3d5d 100644\n--- a/tests/testapp/forms.py\n+++ b/tests/testapp/forms.py\n@@ -9,6 +9,10 @@\n from djmoney.forms import MoneyField\n \n from .models import (\n+    ModelWithCallableCurrencyChoices,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefault,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefaultAndDefaultCurrency,\n+    ModelWithCallableDefaultCurrency,\n     ModelWithDefaultAsString,\n     ModelWithDefaultPrecision,\n     ModelWithValidation,\n@@ -39,6 +43,30 @@ class Meta:\n         fields = (\"money\",)\n \n \n+class MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefault(forms.ModelForm):\n+    class Meta:\n+        model = ModelWithCallableDefault\n+        fields = (\"money\",)\n+\n+\n+class MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefaultCurrency(forms.ModelForm):\n+    class Meta:\n+        model = ModelWithCallableDefaultCurrency\n+        fields = (\"money\",)\n+\n+\n+class MoneyModelFormWithCallableCurrencyChoices(forms.ModelForm):\n+    class Meta:\n+        model = ModelWithCallableCurrencyChoices\n+        fields = (\"money\",)\n+\n+\n+class MoneyModelFormWithCallableDefaultAndCallableDefaultCurrency(forms.ModelForm):\n+    class Meta:\n+        model = ModelWithCallableDefaultAndDefaultCurrency\n+        fields = (\"money\",)\n+\n+\n class NullableModelForm(forms.ModelForm):\n     class Meta:\n         model = NullMoneyFieldModel\ndiff --git a/tests/testapp/models.py b/tests/testapp/models.py\nindex 83766a6a8..af503ab76 100644\n--- a/tests/testapp/models.py\n+++ b/tests/testapp/models.py\n@@ -24,6 +24,22 @@\n     register = lambda _: None  # noqa\n \n \n+def get_default():\n+    return Money(\"0.00\", settings.TEST_DEFAULT_CURRENCY)\n+\n+\n+def get_default_currency():\n+    return settings.TEST_DEFAULT_CURRENCY\n+\n+\n+def get_currency_choices():\n+    a_list = [\"DKK\", \"USD\"]\n+    if settings.TEST_DEFAULT_CURRENCY not in a_list:\n+        a_list.append(settings.TEST_DEFAULT_CURRENCY)\n+    a_list.sort()\n+    return [(code, code) for code in a_list]\n+\n+\n class ModelWithVanillaMoneyField(models.Model):\n     money = MoneyField(max_digits=10, decimal_places=2)\n     second_money = MoneyField(max_digits=10, decimal_places=2, default=0.0, default_currency=\"EUR\")\n@@ -228,3 +244,27 @@ class ModelWithDefaultPrecision(models.Model):\n \n class ModelWithNullDefaultOnNonNullableField(models.Model):\n     money = MoneyField(max_digits=10, decimal_places=2, default=None, default_currency=None)\n+\n+\n+class ModelWithCallableDefault(models.Model):\n+\n+    money = MoneyField(max_digits=10, decimal_places=2, default=get_default, blank=True)\n+\n+\n+class ModelWithCallableDefaultCurrency(models.Model):\n+\n+    money = MoneyField(max_digits=10, decimal_places=2, default_currency=get_default_currency)\n+\n+\n+class ModelWithCallableDefaultAndDefaultCurrency(models.Model):\n+\n+    money = MoneyField(\n+        max_digits=10, decimal_places=2, default=get_default, default_currency=get_default_currency, blank=True\n+    )\n+\n+\n+class ModelWithCallableCurrencyChoices(models.Model):\n+\n+    money = MoneyField(\n+        max_digits=10, decimal_places=2, default_currency=get_default_currency, currency_choices=get_currency_choices\n+    )\n", "problem_statement": "Specify a callable for default_currency\nRef: https://github.com/inventree/InvenTree/issues/1674\r\n\r\nIt would be great to be able to specify a callable for the `default_currency` parameter on a model `MoneyField`. I would like to be able to change the `BASE_CURRENCY` in settings.py without requiring migrations to the database schema.\r\n\r\nCurrently it seems that each time the `BASE_CURRENCY` parameter is changed, a new migration is generated for each and every model which has a `DjangoMoney` field.\r\n\r\nIs there a simple way around this? Or is supporting a callable required before I can do this?\n", "hints_text": "+1 for this. Came here to create the same request. It would be really useful to have the ability to use a callable to set the default value and currency for `MoneyField` . This would allow us to set different defaults for different users.\nI also just came here to support this proposal. Hard realization that I'm also maintaining the project, so now I feel like I have to implement it, too \ud83d\ude02 (a bit hard to find the time, though)\n\nProposing something like this:\n\nAdd test models with combinations of defaults for MoneyField:\n\n(settings.CURRENCY should be defined in the tests)\n\ndefault=callable\ndefault_currency=(unset)\n\ndefault=0\ndefault_currency=callable\n\ndefault=callable\ndefault_currency=callable\n\nI don't think we need to do anything about the callables being incompatible, just have to verify/assert that the migrations that are generated make sense.\nWe need the whole same bag of tests / fixes for `currency_choices=a_callable`, since the CurrencyField generated now has a serialized currency list.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "+1 for this. Came here to create the same request. It would be really useful to have the ability to use a callable to set the default value and currency for `MoneyField` . This would allow us to set different defaults for different users.\nI also just came here to support this proposal. Hard realization that I'm also maintaining the project, so now I feel like I have to implement it, too \ud83d\ude02 (a bit hard to find the time, though)\n\nProposing something like this:\n\nAdd test models with combinations of defaults for MoneyField:\n\n(settings.CURRENCY should be defined in the tests)\n\ndefault=callable\ndefault_currency=(unset)\n\ndefault=0\ndefault_currency=callable\n\ndefault=callable\ndefault_currency=callable\n\nI don't think we need to do anything about the callables being incompatible, just have to verify/assert that the migrations that are generated make sense.\nWe need the whole same bag of tests / fixes for `currency_choices=a_callable`, since the CurrencyField generated now has a serialized currency list.\nAfter playing around with an implementation, I'm getting pretty sure that neither of these are good/possible:\n\n```python\n# default is callable, but default_currency isn't. This makes it hard for us to create our\n# currency field as a field that's serialization-friendly, since it requires a dynamic\n# function to return the currency from the default's callable.\n# HOWEVER, since we can have a default currency defined in settings, this can still be allowed.\nmoney = MoneyField(default=some_callable)\n\n# default_currency defined but default IS NOT defined\n# This is the most impossible one!\n# We cannot add a currency to the default amount since the currency is a callable, so this would\n# ALWAYS AND IN ALL CASES require a dynamic callable (which cannot be serialized = migrations fail)\nmoney = MoneyField(default_currency=some_callable, default=0)\n```\n\nWhy? Because in both cases, defining the default of either the currency or amount field depends on what the callable returns. That would require a dynamic callable, and that cannot be serialized.\n\nThese should be possible:\n\n```python\n# Both defaults are callable - this should be the preferred standard.\nmoney = MoneyField(default=some_callable, default_currency=another_callable)\n\n# default_currency is callable and default is a hard-coded Money object with a currency\n# This will hardly make sense, but it can be used to provide a number as a value without\n# any currency.\nmoney = MoneyField(default_currency=some_callable, default=Money(0, \"USD\"))\n\n# default_currency is callable and the other one isn't defined / NOT_PROVIDED\n# - this is a bit more meaningful, since it allows forms to pre-select the default\n# currency\nmoney = MoneyField(default_currency=some_callable, default=None)\n```\n\n\nThis wasn't fully fixed: It seems like the callables for `currency_choices` and `currency_default` are called+serialized in the auto-generated `CurrencyField`. That's no good!\nAh, I understand the bug I'm seeing now: The default behavior of a MoneyField is to have `default_currency=DEFAULT_CURRENCY` - meaning that when the default is changed in settings\n\nhttps://github.com/django-money/django-money/blob/main/djmoney/settings.py#L12-L12\n\n...then a migration is created.\n\nI think we need to change this behavior, too. That'll be a big benefit to anyone using this app.\nHaven been testing out 3.6.0b1 and it's working well. I've tried to change the default project settings both for default currency and currency choices, and it doesn't cause new migrations.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/b8b36e6a00a7de870bf7ab33874fb16f049d3404", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/c56d6c96a701eeb17975ac4de13926ba7327f0f6", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/c08ccee0291a546534a253de17896fdd5461300f", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/a48870228d772a877950b25faa6b40fd1da2bd3c", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/02eaf481994779b56d3e21d2b403e06470079bd3", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/d702d7aab66efc788d8ec514ff6faa90900a6199", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/cabd2907946becf61ab20bf153b24e98e48fe771", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/f17af29fce843ed87234c7003a6ff0e18515d14c", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/38830d569cbcc1e43e3cf5b0ecae885e61818362", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/147f51c8a31893e702d8d1b82d704a2d2016cfd8", "https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/9ca781daf0e75d608b030aa1edee41db9e486222"], "created_at": "2025-08-30T23:16:44Z"}
{"repo": "django-money/django-money", "pull_number": 804, "instance_id": "django-money__django-money-804", "issue_numbers": [781], "base_commit": "54de5e3fd8f03f3ee1e674d9df600525474a3c06", "patch": "diff --git a/.github/workflows/main.yml b/.github/workflows/main.yml\nindex 4db9424fc..7989cf40f 100644\n--- a/.github/workflows/main.yml\n+++ b/.github/workflows/main.yml\n@@ -37,10 +37,6 @@ jobs:\n       fail-fast: false\n       matrix:\n         include:\n-          - python: '3.8'\n-            tox_env: django42-py38\n-          - python: '3.9'\n-            tox_env: django42-py39\n           - python: '3.10'\n             tox_env: django42-py310\n           - python: '3.10'\ndiff --git a/djmoney/__init__.py b/djmoney/__init__.py\nindex dc9e18d06..6361d12fe 100644\n--- a/djmoney/__init__.py\n+++ b/djmoney/__init__.py\n@@ -1,1 +1,1 @@\n-__version__ = \"3.6.0b2\"\n+__version__ = \"3.6.0b3\"\ndiff --git a/docs/changes.rst b/docs/changes.rst\nindex 94be053cd..f9aec7b5c 100644\n--- a/docs/changes.rst\n+++ b/docs/changes.rst\n@@ -18,6 +18,10 @@ Changelog\n \n - Migrate to pyproject.toml and uv :github-issue:`791` (:github-user:`browniebroke`)\n \n+**Removed**\n+\n+- Python 3.8 and 3.9 support was dropped to give way for typehints :github-issue:`781` (:github-user:`benjaoming`)\n+\n \n `3.5.4`_ - 2025-04-17\n ---------------------\ndiff --git a/pyproject.toml b/pyproject.toml\nindex 0e82cbbf2..a804e7a1f 100644\n--- a/pyproject.toml\n+++ b/pyproject.toml\n@@ -8,7 +8,7 @@ dynamic = [\"version\"]\n description = \"Adds support for using money and currency fields in django models and forms. Uses py-moneyed as the money implementation.\"\n readme = \"README.rst\"\n license = { text = \"BSD\" }\n-requires-python = \">=3.8\"\n+requires-python = \">=3.10\"\n maintainers = [\n     { name = \"Greg Reinbach\", email = \"greg@reinbach.com\" },\n     { name = \"Benjamin Balder Bach\", email = \"benjamin@overtag.dk\" },\n@@ -30,8 +30,6 @@ classifiers = [\n     \"Operating System :: OS Independent\",\n     \"Programming Language :: Python\",\n     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3\",\n-    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.8\",\n-    \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.9\",\n     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.10\",\n     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.11\",\n     \"Programming Language :: Python :: 3.12\",\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Typehints + bump requirements to Python 3.9 and Django 4.2\nIt seems like we could make a lot of gains by introducing typehints.\r\n\r\nThis however requires to bump to Django 4.2 and Python 3.9.\r\n\r\n* Django 4.2: Because it's the only currently supported version of Django and it supports Python 3.10\r\n* Python 3.10: Because it supports the most conventional type annotations\r\n* Remove old stubs\r\n\r\nAny further modernization is great, but not required.\r\n\r\n**It seems obvious that handling sensitive data like Money can benefit from type hints.**\r\n\r\nThoughts?\r\n\r\nRelated: #780\n", "hints_text": "@benjaoming I think this is really needed, a lot of python projects use typehints + a type checker nowadays, without types mypy would constantly complain about using untyped django-money objects.\nAgreed @notypecheck \ud83d\udcaf \nIs there any progress on this one?\n@bvedad yes! now is a good time to pick up on this! I think we have a considerable Python backlog, and we should go for Python 3.10 in the next release.\n\nI just started some beta releases for django-money 3.6, so I would like to just cut the Python 3.8 and 3.9 support already.\n\n@Stranger6667 any thoughts or a thumbs-up? \ud83d\ude0a\n\n", "all_hints_text": "@benjaoming I think this is really needed, a lot of python projects use typehints + a type checker nowadays, without types mypy would constantly complain about using untyped django-money objects.\nAgreed @notypecheck \ud83d\udcaf \nIs there any progress on this one?\n@bvedad yes! now is a good time to pick up on this! I think we have a considerable Python backlog, and we should go for Python 3.10 in the next release.\n\nI just started some beta releases for django-money 3.6, so I would like to just cut the Python 3.8 and 3.9 support already.\n\n@Stranger6667 any thoughts or a thumbs-up? \ud83d\ude0a\nNow released as 3.6.0b3\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/4735ce4e6b1f6ae1c476ded512fbb86b965715c3"], "created_at": "2025-09-03T21:05:29Z"}
{"repo": "django-money/django-money", "pull_number": 808, "instance_id": "django-money__django-money-808", "issue_numbers": [793], "base_commit": "57f6d8ccb8a89476379656b1b7333e8195d2d767", "patch": "diff --git a/.github/workflows/upgrader.yml b/.github/workflows/upgrader.yml\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 00000000..ff24e6bc\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/.github/workflows/upgrader.yml\n@@ -0,0 +1,29 @@\n+name: Upgrader\n+\n+on:\n+  workflow_dispatch:\n+  schedule:\n+    - cron: \"49 5 8 * *\"\n+\n+jobs:\n+  upgrade:\n+    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n+    permissions:\n+      contents: write\n+      pull-requests: write\n+    steps:\n+      - uses: actions/checkout@v5\n+      - uses: astral-sh/setup-uv@v6\n+        with:\n+          python-version: 3.13\n+      - run: rm uv.lock\n+      - run: uv lock\n+      - uses: peter-evans/create-pull-request@v7\n+        with:\n+          branch: update/uv-lock\n+          title: \"Upgrade dependencies from uv.lock\"\n+          commit-message: \"Upgrade dependencies\"\n+          body: |\n+            Upgrade dependencies from lock file by deleting `uv.lock` and generating it again.\n+\n+            Note that CI job did NOT run due to [the default `GITHUB_TOKEN` limitations](https://github.com/peter-evans/create-pull-request#token). To trigger it, close this pull request and re-open it.\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Evaluate if uv.lock should stay\nhttps://github.com/django-money/django-money/pull/791 introduced uv.lock and we should revisit this choice to know if we really need a lock file in a distributed package or not.\n\n@browniebroke has a suggestion on using GitHub Actions to keep the file updated: https://github.com/django-money/django-money/pull/791#issuecomment-2831085676\n", "hints_text": "It's should be ok to keep `uv.lock` there, it pins your regular and dev dependencies when developing the package, and when distributing users would install dependencies specified under `pyproject.toml/dependencies`, e.g. `typing-extensions>=4.12.2`.\nHi @notypecheck \ud83d\udc4b what is the point of having pinned development if package users don't use them? (I'm asking the question out of genuine interest)\n\nI think there needs to be some kind of pro/con list:\n\nPro:\n\n* Developers can reproduce their environment\n\nCon:\n\n* Need to add extra chores, GitHub actions and noise around updating the .lock file. PRs, CI runs, merge conflicts etc.\n* User issues may go unnoticed since users are not using pinned requirements\nI see 2 main separate cases, with a few examples\n\n### One of your dev dep releases a new version that is incompatible with the project (e.g. pytest)\n\n- A contributor comes in and tries to submit a new feature/fix for a completely unrelated thing. They checkout the repo and start the run the test, notice that the test fails with an obscure error. They either give up, or waste time debugging this.\n- A maintainer makes a change, all works fine locally, but break on CI - takes time to debug why and eventually realise that something got upgraded under your feet.\n\nIn both cases, it slow down contributions, and there is no impact to your users (this is just some local/dev deps to the repo which are involved)\n\n### One of the main deps releases a new version that is incompatible with the project \n\nYou may not notice for a while, even without pinned dependencies. You'd have to run CI on this project to notice the breakage, which depending on the frequency of the contributions might be too slow. In my experience, you're more likely to have your users notice before your CI does.\n\n", "all_hints_text": "It's should be ok to keep `uv.lock` there, it pins your regular and dev dependencies when developing the package, and when distributing users would install dependencies specified under `pyproject.toml/dependencies`, e.g. `typing-extensions>=4.12.2`.\nHi @notypecheck \ud83d\udc4b what is the point of having pinned development if package users don't use them? (I'm asking the question out of genuine interest)\n\nI think there needs to be some kind of pro/con list:\n\nPro:\n\n* Developers can reproduce their environment\n\nCon:\n\n* Need to add extra chores, GitHub actions and noise around updating the .lock file. PRs, CI runs, merge conflicts etc.\n* User issues may go unnoticed since users are not using pinned requirements\nI see 2 main separate cases, with a few examples\n\n### One of your dev dep releases a new version that is incompatible with the project (e.g. pytest)\n\n- A contributor comes in and tries to submit a new feature/fix for a completely unrelated thing. They checkout the repo and start the run the test, notice that the test fails with an obscure error. They either give up, or waste time debugging this.\n- A maintainer makes a change, all works fine locally, but break on CI - takes time to debug why and eventually realise that something got upgraded under your feet.\n\nIn both cases, it slow down contributions, and there is no impact to your users (this is just some local/dev deps to the repo which are involved)\n\n### One of the main deps releases a new version that is incompatible with the project \n\nYou may not notice for a while, even without pinned dependencies. You'd have to run CI on this project to notice the breakage, which depending on the frequency of the contributions might be too slow. In my experience, you're more likely to have your users notice before your CI does.\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/6e837522ae2832e61a60d349693d30a065bdd7db"], "created_at": "2025-10-01T18:54:27Z"}
{"repo": "django-money/django-money", "pull_number": 813, "instance_id": "django-money__django-money-813", "issue_numbers": [812], "base_commit": "74eaa110bbfdc9da6cec216a2c8bc845d97b5d96", "patch": "diff --git a/djmoney/__init__.py b/djmoney/__init__.py\nindex 6361d12f..85197cb4 100644\n--- a/djmoney/__init__.py\n+++ b/djmoney/__init__.py\n@@ -1,1 +1,1 @@\n-__version__ = \"3.6.0b3\"\n+__version__ = \"3.6.0\"\ndiff --git a/docs/changes.rst b/docs/changes.rst\nindex f9aec7b5..57288ae0 100644\n--- a/docs/changes.rst\n+++ b/docs/changes.rst\n@@ -2,13 +2,14 @@ Changelog\n =========\n \n \n-`3.6b2`_ - 2025-09-01\n----------------------\n+`3.6`_ - 2026-01-27\n+-------------------\n \n **Added**\n \n - Support for callable ``default`` and ``currency_default``, and ``currency_choices`` :github-issue:`683` (:github-user:`benjaoming`)\n - Add ``backend`` kwarg to ``convert_money`` function :github-issue:`787` (:github-user:`heckad`)\n+- Add getting a limit value from a callable :github-issue:`810` (:github-user:`heckad`)\n \n **Fixed**\n \n@@ -875,7 +876,10 @@ wrapping with ``money_manager``.\n \n - Initial public release\n \n-.. _3.6b2: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5.4...HEAD\n+..\n+  .. _develop: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.6...HEAD\n+\n+.. _3.6: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5.4...3.6\n .. _3.5.4: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5.4...3.5.3\n .. _3.5.3: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5.3...3.5.2\n .. _3.5.2: https:///github.com/django-money/django-money/compare/3.5.2...3.5.1\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Any plans to do new release?\n[This commit](https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/74eaa110bbfdc9da6cec216a2c8bc845d97b5d96) is very important to us. When is a new release planned?\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Looking at it now!\nMany thanks for this!\n@heckad really sorry for the long wait, if you're interested in the future prospects of django-money, feel free to drop me an email\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/django-money/django-money/commit/04e03af932f8a22b3e7e62640c9bf6d92082322f"], "created_at": "2026-01-27T21:58:19Z"}
